\begin_layout Abstract
\noindent
This paper presents a new Monte-Carlo methodology to forecast the crude
 oil production of Norway and the U.K.
 based on the current/past performances of individual oil fields.
 By extrapolating the future production of these fields and the frequency
 of new discoveries, the oil production of these countries can be forecasted.
 The results indicate that standard methodologies tend to underestimate
 remaining oil reserves.
 A comparison of the model to those methodologies is made by making predictions
 with the full data and a back-test starting in 2008.
 It shows that the model gives a better description of the evolution of
 the oil production.
\end_layout

