\begin_layout Subsubsection
Back-testing & Error
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To determine how well the extrapolation based on the stretched exponential
 predicts the future production, a complete back-testing has been performed
 on each field.
 A single back-test is made as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The production data 
\begin_inset Formula $\{p_{0},\,\ldots,\, p_{N}\}$
\end_inset

 of the field is truncated at a certain date in the past 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau\in\{0,\,\ldots,\, N\}$
\end_inset

.
 Where 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 is in months since production start of the field.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The extrapolation
\begin_inset Formula $f(t)$
\end_inset

 is made based on the truncated data 
\begin_inset Formula $\{p_{0},\,\ldots,\, p_{\tau}\}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The future production predicted by the extrapolation 
\begin_inset Formula $f(t)$
\end_inset

 can be compared to the actual production from the date 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 in the past up to now 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{f}=N$
\end_inset

.
 The extrapolated total production can be computed as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P_{e}(\tau)=\int_{\tau}^{\tau_{f}}f(t)dt
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and the relative error is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
e(\tau)=\frac{P_{e}(\tau)-\sum_{i=\tau}^{\tau_{f}}p_{i}}{P_{e}(\tau)},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where both are a function of the truncation time 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Computing this back test for every month in the past since the field starting
 decaying, yields a plot showing the evolution of the relative error over
 time 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "oesberg-error"

\end_inset

.
 By construction, the relative error will tend to zero as the truncation
 time 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 goes to the present.
 Nonetheless, it is a uself indicator for the stability of the extrapolation.
 As can been seen for the Oseberg field, the relative error on future production
 remained fairly stable during the past decade.
\end_layout

