\begin_layout Subsubsection
Aggregate error
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Once the individual fields have been extrapolated in the sense of formula
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:extrapolation"

\end_inset

, the aim is to compute the extrapolation for the country.
 While it is straightforward to sum the extrapolations of the individual
 fields to obtain the expected production, some care has to be taken with
 respect to the confidence interval on the production at the country level.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As shown later in section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Results"

\end_inset

, the same extrapolation including a complete monthly back-test of total
 future production has been performed at the country level and the resulting
 relative error is much smaller than the average error observed on the individua
l fields.
 To account for this observation, the assumption made is that the relative
 error between individual fields is uncorrelated.
 Therefore, the fields can be considered as a portfolio of assets with a
 return given by their extrapolation 
\begin_inset Formula $p(t)$
\end_inset

 (eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:extrapolation"

\end_inset

) and a risk given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{field}$
\end_inset

 (eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:field-risk"

\end_inset

).
 This means that the risk at the country level from the extrapolated production
 is to be computed as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sigma_{country}^{2}=\frac{1}{\#fields}\sum_{field\in fields}\sigma_{field}^{2}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Intuitively, this models well the fact that the uncorrelated errors among
 fields will mostly cancel out.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Discovery rate of new fields
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:Discovery-rate-of"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Knowing the future production rate of existing fields is not enough as new
 fields will be discovered in the future.
 The model describing the discovery rate of new fields should satisfy two
 fundamental observations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The rate of new discoveries should tend to zero as time goes to infinity.
 This is a consequence of the finiteness of the number of oil fields.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The rate of new discoveries should depend on the size of the oil fields.
 As of today, giant oil fields are discovered much less frequently than
 dwarfs.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Discoveries modeled as logistic growth
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:Discoveries-modeled-as"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A natural choice for such a model is a non-homogenous Poisson process.
 The Poisson process is a process that generates independent events at a
 rate 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

.
 It is inhomogeneous if the rate is time-dependent, 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\rightarrow\lambda(t)$
\end_inset

.
 The standard way to measure 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda(t)$
\end_inset

 is to find a functional form for 
\begin_inset Formula $N(t)$
\end_inset

, the statistical average of the cumulative number of events (discoveries)
 up to time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

.
 Then, 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda(t)$
\end_inset

 is simply 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{dN(t)}{dt}$
\end_inset

.
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "rate_of_discovery"

\end_inset

 shows 
\begin_inset Formula $N(t)$
\end_inset

 for Norwegian fields classified according to their size.
 The logistic curve is a good fit to the data (integral form of equation
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "logistic"

\end_inset

).
 This implies that after an initial increase, the rate of new discoveries
 reaches a peak followed by a decrease until no more oil fields are to be
 found, consistent with our fundamental observations.
 This same approach has already been successfully applied to estimate the
 number of daily active users on Zynga 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Forro 2012"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As the discovery and production dynamics are not independent of the field
 size, the fields have been split into two groups: dwarfs and giants.
 Unfortunately, the two logistic curves thus obtained are highly sensitive
 to the splitting size.
 This results from the major issue, when fitting a logistic curve to data,
 that the carrying capacity can not be determined if the data does not already
 exhibit the slow down in growth from reaching the carrying capacity.
 However, it is mentioned in the literature that often dwarf fields have
 already been discovered a long time ago, but their production has been
 postponed for economical reasons 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "p. 378"
key "Lynch 2002"

\end_inset

.
 Therefore, it is expected that the large oil fields have mostly been found
 and produced, and that future discoveries will mostly be made up of dwarf
 fields.
 Consequently, the splitting size has been picked as small as possible in
 order to maximize the number of giant fields but large enough to avoid
 recent discoveries:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Dwarfs
\series default
: Fields which produced less than 
\begin_inset Formula $50\cdot10^{6}$
\end_inset

 barrels.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Giants
\series default
: Fields which produced more than 
\begin_inset Formula $50\cdot10^{6}$
\end_inset

 barrels.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The resulting plot shown in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "rate_of_discovery"

\end_inset

 pictures the dynamics: giant oil fields have mostly been found while the
 discovery process for dwarf fields is still ongoing.
 The logistic growth curve fit to the giant discoveries is well constrained,
 however the fit for the dwarfs is poorly constrained.
 As can be seen on figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "rate_of_discovery"

\end_inset

, the carrying capacity 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 of the logistic growth model is not well constrained by the available data.
 A large spectrum of values for 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 can lead to an equally good fit of the data.
 Therefore, a method described in section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
