\begin_layout Standard
The goal is to compute an expected oil production coming from future discoveries
, which requires to combine the steps described in sections 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:Discoveries-modeled-as"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:Likelihood-function-for"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The method described in section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:Likelihood-function-for"

\end_inset

 yields probabilities for the total number of fields (including the not
 yet discovered fields) in each size bins (called a scenario).
 However, this likelihood method does not give the time distribution of
 future discoveries.
 The aim is to use the likelihood function to generate scenarios with their
 respective occurrence probability.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For a given scenario, the carrying capacity 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 (= total number of fields) is given for each size class.
 This is useful, because it resolves the instability in fitting the logistic
 curve to the number of discovered fields.
 The time distribution of the discoveries is then given for each size class
 by the fitted logistic curve.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The actual size of a newly discovered field is generated according to the
 size distribution of the existing fields in its size class.
 The probability distribution function of field sizes in a given size bin
 has been fitted by a stretched exponential function.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The production curve is computed based on the average production curve of
 all existing fields in the same size category.
 The production curves of the existing fields have all been normalized to
 a total production of one and then have been averaged.
 This yields an average production curve including a one standard deviation
 error.
 For a new field, this average production curve is than multiplied by the
 size of the field.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Superposing the production curves results in the expected production curve
 from future oil field for a given scenario.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As the total parameter space is too large to be sampled entirely, a Monte
 Carlo technique is applied to compute the expected production from future
 discoveries and its standard deviation.
 In a nutshell, the algorithm works as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Draw a scenario based on its probability.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Compute the time distribution of new discoveries by fitting a logistic curve
 for each size class.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
For each discovery generate a size and the resulting production curve based
 on the size distribution and production curves of existing fields.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Superpose all the production curves.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Repeat and average over all drawn scenarios.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The result is the expected production curve of future oil field discoveries.
 The distribution of generated scenarios yields the confidence interval.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In order to account for the new fields discussed in section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:Regular,-irregular-and"

\end_inset

, which are already discovered but did not yet enter the decay phase, the
 simulated production resulting from new discoveries has been shifted to
 the date in the past where it matches the current production from new fields.
\end_layout

