\begin_layout Section
Conclusion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This paper presented a Monte-Carlo based methodology to forecast future
 oil production.
 By extending the oil production of current fields into the future and modeling
 the discovery rate of new fields, the future oil production of Norway and
 the U.K.
 could be forecasted.
 These forecasts are significantly different from the ones obtained with
 a standard extrapolation.
 Indeed, our model forecasts 30% to 40% more remaining oil reserves than
 the standard extrapolation.
 The back-test performed on the time period between 2008 and 2014 confirmed
 that the Monte-Carlo based model better captured the production dynamics.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The results are hopeful, as they make it highly likely that the decay of
 Norwegian and U.K.
 oil production will be much slower then one would expect from a standard
 extrapolation.
 Nonetheless, to maintain current levels of oil consumption in the European
 Union, more of it will have to be imported from outside Europe, as the
 imports from Norway will vanish (currently accounting for 11% of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "European oil imports"

\end_inset

) and the U.K.
 will need to import more oil.
 Therefore, the risk emanating of oil imports from less reliable producers
 and the exposure to competitors for this oil will increase.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Considering the risk of strong oil price fluctuations due to small supply
 shortcomings and the economic impact this has 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Lutz 2012"

\end_inset

, it is primordial for Europe to reduce its oil dependency by energy savings
 and using substitutes.
\end_layout

